{"title_page": "Cumbria", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Cumbia|Umbria|Cambria|Cambrian|Cumberland}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{short description|Ceremonial (geographic) county of England, UK}}\n{{infobox English county\n| official_name           = Cumbria\n| flag_image              = [[File:County Flag of Cumbria.svg|100px]]\n| flag_link               = Flag of Cumbria\n| arms_image              = [[File:Cumbria County Council coat of arms.jpg|100px]]\n| arms_link               = Coat of arms of Cumbria\n| motto                   = \"''Ad Montes Oculos Levavi''\" (\"[[Psalm 121|I have lifted up mine eyes unto the hills]]\")\n| locator_map             = [[File:Cumbria UK locator map 2010.svg|200px|Cumbria within England]]\n| coordinates             = {{Coord|54|30|N|3|15|W|type:adm2nd_region:GB-CMA|display=title,inline}}\n| region                  = [[North West England|North West]]\n| established_date        = 1 April 1974\n| established_by          = [[Local Government Act 1972]]\n| lord_lieutenant_office  = Lord Lieutenant of Cumbria\n| lord_lieutenant_name    = Claire Hensman\n| high_sheriff_office     = High Sheriff of Cumbria\n| high_sheriff_name       = Marcia Reid Fotheringham, JP <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cumbria.gov.uk/council-democracy/councillors-democracy-elections/lordlieutenant/sheriff.asp|title=High Sheriff|publisher=Cumbria County Council|accessdate= 16 April 2019}}</ref> (2019\u20132020)\n| area_total_km2          = 6768\n| area_total_rank         = 3rd\n| WB = 97.5 |WI = 0.1 |WG = 0.1 |OW = 1.1 |MWBC = 0.1 |MWBA = 0.1 |MWA =0.2 |OM = 0.1 |I =0.2 |P =0.1 |B =0.1 |C =0.2 |OA =0.2 |BA = 0.1 |O =0.1\n| county_council          = [[Cumbria County Council]]\n| admin_hq                = [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]]\n| area_council_km2        = 6768\n| area_council_rank       = 2nd\n| iso_code                = GB-CMA\n| ons_code                = 16\n| gss_code                = E10000006\t\n| nuts_code               = UKD11, UKD12\n| districts_map           = [[File:CumbriaNumbered.png]]\n| districts_list          = \n# [[Borough of Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow-in-Furness]]\n# [[South Lakeland]]\n# [[Borough of Copeland|Copeland]]\n# [[Allerdale]]\n# [[Eden District|Eden]]\n# [[City of Carlisle]]\n| MPs                     = [[List of Parliamentary constituencies in Cumbria|List of MPs]]\n| police                  = [[Cumbria Constabulary]]\n| website                 = {{URL|www.cumbria.gov.uk}}\n}}\n'''Cumbria''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|\u028c|m|b|r|i|\u0259}} {{respell|KUM|bree|\u0259}}) is a [[ceremonial counties of England|ceremonial]] and [[non-metropolitan county]] in [[North West England]]. The county and [[Cumbria County Council]], its [[local government]], came into existence in 1974 after the passage of the [[Local Government Act 1972]]. Cumbria's [[county town]] is [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]], in the north of the county, and the only other major urban area is [[Barrow-in-Furness]] on the southwestern tip of the county.\n\nThe county of Cumbria consists of six [[Districts of England|districts]] ([[Allerdale]], [[Borough of Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow-in-Furness]], [[City of Carlisle|Carlisle]], [[Borough of Copeland|Copeland]], [[Eden District|Eden]], and [[South Lakeland]]) and in 2008 had a population of just under 500,000 people. Cumbria is one of the most sparsely populated counties in England, with 73.4 people per km<sup>2</sup> (190/sq mi).\n\nCumbria is the second largest county in England by area, and is bounded to the north by the [[Subdivisions of Scotland|Scottish council area]]s of [[Dumfries and Galloway]] and [[Scottish Borders]], to the west by the [[Irish Sea]], to the south by [[Lancashire]], to the southeast by [[North Yorkshire]], and to the east by [[County Durham]] and [[Northumberland]].\n\nCumbria is predominantly rural and contains the [[Lake District]] [[National parks of England and Wales|National Park]], a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]] considered one of England's finest areas of natural beauty, serving as inspiration for artists, writers, and musicians. A large area of the southeast of the county is within the [[Yorkshire Dales National Park]] while the east of the county fringes the [[North Pennines]] [[Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty|AONB]]. Much of Cumbria is mountainous, and it contains every peak in England over {{convert|3000|ft|m}} above sea level, with [[Scafell Pike]] at {{convert|3209|ft|m}} being the highest point of England. An upland, coastal, and rural area, Cumbria's history is characterised by invasions, migration, and settlement, as well as battles and skirmishes between the English and the Scots. Notable historic sites in Cumbria include [[Carlisle Castle]], [[Furness Abbey]], [[Hardknott Roman Fort]], [[Brough Castle]] and [[Hadrian's Wall]] (also a [[World Heritage Site]]).\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of Cumbria}}\n[[File:Castlerigg2.JPG|thumb|left|The [[Castlerigg stone circle]] dates from the late [[Neolithic|Neolithic age]] and was constructed by some of the earliest inhabitants of Cumbria]]\n\nThe county of Cumbria was created in April 1974 through an amalgamation of the [[Administrative counties of England|administrative counties]] of [[Cumberland]] and [[Westmorland]], to which parts of [[Lancashire]] (the area known as [[Furness|Lancashire North of the Sands]]) and the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]] were added.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1972/70/schedule/1|title=Local Government Act 1972|website=www.legislation.gov.uk|access-date=2018-08-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701222339/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1972/70/schedule/1|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Neolithic]] period the area contained an important centre of stone axe production (the so-called [[Langdale axe industry|'Langdale Axe Factory']]), products of which have been found across Great Britain.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-wYOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA60&dq=Langdale+axe+industry#v=onepage&q=Langdale%20axe%20industry&f=false|title=Neolithic Britain: New Stone Age Sites of England, Scotland, and Wales|last=Castleden|first=Rodney|date=1992|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780415058452|access-date=20 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820172803/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-wYOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA60&dq=Langdale+axe+industry&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Langdale%20axe%20industry&f=false|archive-date=20 August 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> During this period [[stone circles]] and [[henges]] were built across the county and today 'Cumbria has one of the largest number of preserved field monuments in England'.<ref>Barrowclough (2010), p. 105.</ref>\n\nWhile not part of the region conquered in the [[Roman conquest of Britain|Romans' initial conquest of Britain]] in AD 43, most of modern-day Cumbria was later conquered in response to a revolt deposing the Roman-aligned ruler of the [[Brigantes]] in AD 69.<ref>Shotter (2014), p.5</ref> The Romans built a number of fortifications in the area during their occupation, the most famous being [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]] [[Hadrian's Wall]] which passes through northern Cumbria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/430|title=Frontiers of the Roman Empire|last=Centre|first=UNESCO World Heritage|website=whc.unesco.org|access-date=2018-08-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820203449/https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/430|archive-date=20 August 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the period of British history known as [[Roman Britain]] ({{circa|AD 410}}) the inhabitants of Cumbria were [[Cumbric]]-speaking native [[Romano-British culture|Romano-Britons]] who were probably descendants of the [[Brigantes]] and [[Carvetii]] (sometimes considered to be a sub-tribe of the Brigantes) that the [[Roman Empire]] had conquered in about AD 85.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}} Based on inscriptional evidence from the area, the Roman ''{{lang|la|[[civitas]]}}'' of the Carvetii seems to have covered portions of Cumbria. The names ''Cumbria'', ''{{lang|cy|Cymru}}'' (the native [[Welsh language|Welsh]] name for [[Wales]]), ''Cambria'', and ''Cumberland'' are derived from the name these people gave themselves, *''kombroges'' in [[Common Brittonic]], which originally meant \"compatriots\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?search=cymru&searchmode=none |title=Cymric |work=Online Etymological Dictionary |accessdate=25 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100427060757/http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?search=cymru&searchmode=none |archive-date=27 April 2010 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=Davies>{{cite book |last=Davies |first=John |title=A History of Wales |publisher=Penguin Books |origyear=1990 |year=2007 |pages=68\u201369}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Cumbria was previously believed to have formed the core of the [[Early Middle Ages]] [[Celtic Britons|Brittonic]] kingdom of [[Rheged]], more recent discoveries near [[Galloway]] appear to contradict this.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The lost Dark Age kingdom of Rheged : the discovery of a royal stronghold at Trusty's Hill, Galloway|last=Ronan|first=Toolis|others=Bowles, Christopher R.|isbn=9781785703126|location=Oxford|oclc=967457029|date = 2017-01-31}}</ref> For the rest of the first millennium, Cumbria was contested by several entities who warred over the area, including the Brythonic Celtic [[Kingdom of Strathclyde]] and the [[Angles|Anglian]] [[kingdom of Northumbria]]. Most of modern-day Cumbria was a principality in the Kingdom of [[Scotland]] at the time of the [[Norman conquest of England]] in 1066 and thus was excluded from the [[Domesday Book]] survey of 1086. In 1092 the region was invaded by [[William II of England|William II]] and incorporated into England.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Norman rule in Cumbria, 1092-1136|last=1954-|first=Sharpe, Richard|date=2006|publisher=Cumberland and Westmorland Antiquarian and Archaeological Society|isbn=978-1873124437|oclc=122952827}}</ref> Nevertheless, the region was dominated by the many [[Anglo-Scottish Wars]] of the latter [[Middle Ages]] and [[early modern period]] and the associated [[Border Reivers]] who exploited the dynamic political situation of the region.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tuck|first=J.A.|date=January 1986|title=The Emergence of a Northern Nobility, 1250\u20131400|journal=Northern History|volume=22|issue=1|pages=1\u201317|doi=10.1179/007817286790616516|issn=0078-172X}}</ref> There were at least three [[siege of Carlisle (disambiguation)|sieges of Carlisle]] fought between England and Scotland, and two further sieges during the [[Jacobite risings]].\n\nAfter the Jacobite Risings of the eighteenth century, Cumbria became a more stable place and, as in the rest of [[Northern England]], the [[Industrial Revolution]] caused a large growth in urban populations. In particular, the west-coast towns of [[Workington]], [[Millom]] and [[Barrow-in-Furness]] saw large iron and [[steel mill]]s develop, with Barrow also developing a significant [[shipbuilding]] industry.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Barrow-in-Furness at work : people and industries through the years|last=Gill|first=Jepson|isbn=9781445670041|location=Stroud|oclc=1019605931|date = 2017-11-15}}</ref> [[Kendal]], [[Keswick, Cumbria|Keswick]] and Carlisle all became [[mill town]]s, with textiles, pencils and biscuits among the products manufactured in the region. The early nineteenth century saw the county gain fame as the [[Lake Poets]] and other artists of the [[Romanticism|Romantic movement]], such as [[William Wordsworth]] and [[Samuel Taylor Coleridge]], lived among, and were inspired by, the lakes and mountains of the region. Later, the children's writer [[Beatrix Potter]] also wrote in the region and became a major landowner, granting much of her property to the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] on her death.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The story of Beatrix Potter|last=Sarah|first=Gristwood|isbn=9781909881808|location=London|oclc=951610299|date = 2016-06-09}}</ref> In turn, the large amount of land owned by the National Trust assisted in the formation of the [[Lake District]] [[National parks of England and Wales|National Park]] in 1951, which remains the largest National Park in England and has come to dominate the identity and economy of the county.\n\nThe [[Windscale fire]] of 10 October 1957 was the worst [[Nuclear and radiation accidents and incidents|nuclear accident]] in Great Britain's history.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-12789749 |title=Fukushima - disaster or distraction? |author=Richard Black |date=18 March 2011 |work= |publisher=BBC }}</ref> The county of Cumbria was created in [[Local Government Act 1972|1974]] from the traditional counties of [[Cumberland]] and [[Westmorland]], the Cumberland [[County Borough of Carlisle]], along with the North Lonsdale or [[Furness]] part of [[Lancashire]], usually referred to as \"Lancashire North of the Sands\", (including the [[county borough]] of [[Barrow-in-Furness]]) and, from the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], the [[Sedbergh Rural District]].<ref name=\":2\" /> It is governed by [[Cumbria County Council]].\n\nLocal papers ''[[The Westmorland Gazette]]'' and ''Cumberland and Westmorland Herald'' continue to use the name of their historic county. Other publications, such as local government promotional material, describe the area as \"Cumbria\", as do the [[Lake District]] National Park Authority and most visitors.\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Cumbria SRTM.png|thumb|left|Topographic map of Cumbria]]\nCumbria is the most northwesterly county of England. The northernmost and southernmost points in Cumbria are just west of [[Deadwater, Northumberland]] and [[Walney Island|South Walney]] respectively. [[Kirkby Stephen]] (close to [[Tan Hill, North Yorkshire]]) and [[St Bees Head]] are the most easterly and westerly points of the county. Most of Cumbria is mountainous, with the majority of the county being situated in the Lake District while the [[Pennines]], consisting of the Yorkshire Dales and the North Pennines, lie at the eastern and south-east areas of the county. At {{convert|978|m|ft|0}} [[Scafell Pike]] is the highest point in Cumbria and in England. [[Windermere]] is the largest natural lake in England.\n\nThe [[Lancaster Canal]] runs from Preston into South Cumbria and is partly in use. The [[Ulverston Canal]] which once reached to [[Morecambe Bay]] is maintained although it was closed in 1945. The [[Solway Coast]] and [[Arnside and Silverdale]] [[Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty|AONB's]] lie in the lowland areas of the county, to the north and south respectively.\n\n===Boundaries and divisions===\nCumbria is bordered by the English counties of [[Northumberland]], [[County Durham]], [[North Yorkshire]], [[Lancashire]], and the [[Scotland|Scottish]] council areas of [[Dumfries and Galloway]] and [[Scottish Borders]].\n\nThe boundaries are along the [[Irish Sea]] to [[Morecambe Bay]] in the west, and along the [[Pennines]] to the east. Cumbria's northern boundary stretches from the [[Solway Firth]] from the [[Solway Plain]] eastward along the border with [[Scotland]] to [[Northumberland]].\n\nIt is made up of six [[Districts of England|districts]]: Allerdale, Barrow-in-Furness, Carlisle, Copeland, Eden and South Lakeland. For many administrative purposes Cumbria is divided into three areas&nbsp;\u2014 East, West and South. East consists of the districts of Carlisle and Eden, West&nbsp;consists of Allerdale and Copeland, and South consists of Lakeland and Barrow.\n\nIn January 2007, Cumbria County Council voted in favour of an official bid to scrap the current two-tier system of county and district councils in favour of a new [[Unitary authority|unitary]] Cumbria Council, to be submitted for consideration to the [[Department for Communities and Local Government]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/news/Archive/2007/january/18_01_2007-131242.asp | title=County council votes to pursue a single council for Cumbria | accessdate=24 February 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224110254/http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/news/Archive/2007/january/18_01_2007-131242.asp | archive-date=24 December 2013 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> This was then rejected.\n\nThe county returns six Members of Parliament to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], representing the constituencies of [[Carlisle (UK Parliament constituency)|Carlisle]], [[Penrith and The Border (UK Parliament constituency)|Penrith & The Border]], [[Workington (UK Parliament constituency)|Workington]], [[Copeland (UK Parliament constituency)|Copeland]], [[Westmorland and Lonsdale (UK Parliament constituency)|Westmorland and Lonsdale]] and [[Barrow and Furness (UK Parliament constituency)|Barrow & Furness]].\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:DDH, Barrow-in-Furness.jpg|thumb|right|[[BAE Systems Submarine Solutions]] in Barrow-in-Furness has a workforce of around 5,000 people.]]\nMany large companies and organisations are based in Cumbria. The county council itself employs around 17,000 individuals, while the largest private employer in Cumbria, the [[Sellafield]] nuclear processing site, has a workforce of 10,000.<ref name=Largestemployers1>{{cite web|url=http://www.personneltoday.com/hr/cumbrian-employers-supporting-staff-after-multiple-shooting/|title=Cumbrian employers supporting staff after multiple shooting|publisher=Personneltoday|accessdate=15 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224100104/http://www.personneltoday.com/hr/cumbrian-employers-supporting-staff-after-multiple-shooting/|archive-date=24 December 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all|date=2010-06-03}}</ref> Below is a list of some of the county's largest companies and employers (excluding services such as [[Cumbria Constabulary]], [[Cumbria Fire and Rescue Service|Cumbria Fire and Rescue]] and the [[National Health Service|NHS]] in Cumbria), categorised by district:\n\n'''Allerdale'''\n* [[Associated British Ports Holdings]] own and operate the port of [[Silloth]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abports.co.uk/locations/silloth/|title= Associated British Ports Silloth}}</ref>\n* Plastic film maker [[Innovia Films]] has its headquarters and only UK factory in [[Wigton]], which employs almost 1,000 people and is Wigton's biggest employer.\n* Sealy Beds UK (which is part of the Silentnight Group) own a factory at [[Aspatria]], which employs around 300 people.\n* Carr's Group plc, which is based in [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]], owned a large factory at [[Silloth]] which makes the 'Carr's Breadmaker' range and at one time Carr's farm feeds. This has been sold to [[Whitworths]].\n* Window maker West Port Windows owns a large factory at [[Maryport]], which makes UPVC windows and doors.\n* [[Jennings Brewery|Jennings Brewery Plc]] (now owned by [[Marston's Brewery|Marston's Plc]]), a [[real ale]] brewery, based in [[Cockermouth]].\n* World rally company [[M-Sport]] has its headquarters at [[Dovenby Hall]], [[Dovenby]], near [[Cockermouth]].\n* Swedish paper maker [[Iggesund Paperboard]] has its only UK factory at [[Siddick]], near [[Workington]].\n* U.S.-based [[Eastman Chemical Company]] had a factory at Siddick, near [[Workington]]. It made plastic bottle pellets (PBP) and products for the smoking industry and employed 100 people. This has been subsequently demolished and production transferred overseas.\n* Steel company [[Tata Steel]] owns a cast products plant at [[Workington]], which employs 300 people.\n* [[Eddie Stobart Logistics]] owns a large warehouse at [[Workington]], which was once owned by truck and bus maker [[Leyland Motors|Leyland]].\n* Packaging company [[Amcor]] owns the former [[Alcan]] packaging plant at [[Salterbeck]], [[Workington]].\n* James Walker Ltd, an international high-performance sealing manufacturer, has a large factory at [[Cockermouth]].\n\n'''Barrow-in-Furness'''\n\n* [[BAE Systems Submarine Solutions|Barrow's shipyard]] is one of the UK's largest. [[BAE Systems]] is the current owner and employs around 5,000.<ref name=BAE>{{cite web|url=http://www.baesystems.com/location/BAES_156372/|title=BAE Systems Barrow|publisher=BAE Systems|accessdate=15 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202103440/http://www.baesystems.com/location/BAES_156372|archive-date=2 December 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Associated British Ports Holdings own and operate the [[port of Barrow]].<ref name=ABPHB>{{cite web|url=http://www.abports.co.uk/custinfo/ports/barrow.htm|title=Port of Barrow|publisher=Associated British Ports Holdings|accessdate=18 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927122945/http://www.abports.co.uk/custinfo/ports/barrow.htm|archive-date=27 September 2007|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* The only [[Kimberly-Clark]] mill in the North of England is located in Barrow.<ref name=KimberlyClark>{{cite web |url=http://www.kcprofessional.com/uk/?PageRequest=about_us/locations.htm |title=Kimberly-Clark Barrow |publisher=Kimberly-Clark |accessdate=15 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713141500/http://www.kcprofessional.com/uk/?PageRequest=about_us%2Flocations.htm |archivedate=13 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[James Fisher & Sons]], a large provider of marine engineering services, is based in Barrow.<ref name=JFS>{{cite web|url=http://www.james-fisher.com/|title=James Fisher & Sons Barrow|publisher=James Fisher & Sons|accessdate=15 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120830024340/http://www.james-fisher.com/|archive-date=30 August 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* One of the largest single-site furniture stores in the UK, [[Stollers]], is located in Barrow.<ref name=Stollers>{{cite web|url=http://www.stollers.co.uk/|title=Stollers Barrow|publisher=Stollers|accessdate=16 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301083350/http://www.stollers.co.uk/|archive-date=1 March 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n'''Carlisle'''\n\n* Close to 1,000 people work in one of only two [[Pirelli]] tyre plants in the UK.<ref name=Pirelli>{{cite web|url=http://www.pirelli.co.uk/web/technology/plants/Carlisle.page|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205041435/http://www.pirelli.co.uk/web/technology/plants/Carlisle.page|archivedate=5 December 2008|title=Pirelli Carlisle|publisher=Pirelli|accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Carr's]] is a successful foodstuff and agricultural brand that was established in 1831 in Carlisle.<ref name=\"Carr's\">{{cite web|url=http://www.carrsflour.co.uk/history.html|title=Carr's Carlisle|publisher=Carr's|accessdate=15 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224114106/http://www.carrsflour.co.uk/history.html|archive-date=24 December 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Stobart Group]] owns the [[Carlisle Lake District Airport]] and its rail maintenance business is based in Carlisle.\n* [[Eddie Stobart Logistics|Eddie Stobart]], which is one of the UK's largest logistics companies, used to be headquartered in Carlisle.<ref name=Stobart>{{cite web|url=http://www.stobartgroup.co.uk/|title=Stobart Carlisle|publisher=Stobart|accessdate=15 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722064236/http://www.stobartgroup.co.uk/|archive-date=22 July 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Nestl\u00e9]] operates a factory on the outskirts of Carlisle.<ref name=\"Nestl\u00e9\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ukbusinesspark.co.uk/nestleaa.htm|title=Nestl\u00e9 Carlisle|publisher=ukbusinesspark|accessdate=15 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110818105900/http://www.ukbusinesspark.co.uk/nestleaa.htm|archivedate=18 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Cavaghan & Gray]] (owned by the by [[2 Sisters Food Group]]) is a food manufacturing business based in Carlisle and a significant employer in the city.\n* [[Crown Holdings]] owns two factories in Carlisle, locally known as 'Metal Box'. Both factories make products for the beverage industry.\n* [[Edinburgh Woollen Mill]] announced plans to move their HQ from [[Langholm]], [[Scottish Borders]] to [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-south-scotland-44239890 |title=First minister 'disappointed' by EWM move |access-date=18 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919112357/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-south-scotland-44239890 |archive-date=19 September 2018 |url-status=bot: unknown |df=dmy-all |work=BBC News |date=2018-05-24 }}</ref>\n\n'''Copeland'''\n\n* [[Sellafield]] is the largest private employer in the county; many West Cumbrians have links to the site.<ref name=Sellafield>{{cite web|url=http://www.sellafieldsites.com/|title=Sellafield|publisher=Sellafield|accessdate=16 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704180829/http://www.sellafieldsites.com/|archive-date=4 July 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n'''Eden'''\n\n* [[Center Parcs UK|Center Parcs]] owns a large resort in [[Whinfell Forest]] near Penrith.<ref name=CenterParcs>{{cite web|url=http://www.centerparcs.co.uk/villages/whinfell/index.jsp|title=Center Parcs|publisher=Center Parcs|accessdate=16 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100712105049/http://www.centerparcs.co.uk/villages/whinfell/index.jsp|archive-date=12 July 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Logistics company [[Eddie Stobart Logistics]], own a large transport depot at [[Penrith, Cumbria|Penrith]].\n* National sawdust, animal bedding, bark suppliers and road hauliers A W Jenkinson are headquartered at Clifton, Penrith.\n\n'''South Lakeland'''\n\n* Pharmaceutical company [[GlaxoSmithKline]] operates a large factory in [[Ulverston]].<ref name=GSK>{{cite web|url=http://www.gsk.com/careers/uk-gms-ulverston.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628173048/http://www.gsk.com/careers/uk-gms-ulverston.htm|archivedate=28 June 2012|title=GlaxoSmithKline Ulverston|publisher=GlaxoSmithKline|accessdate=16 July 2010}}</ref>\n* International kitchenware retailer [[Lakeland (company)|Lakeland]] has its headquarters and flagship store in [[Windermere, Cumbria (town)|Windermere]].<ref name=Lakeland>{{cite web|url=http://www.lakeland.co.uk/stores/windermere|title=Lakeland Windermere|publisher=Lakeland|accessdate=16 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110505024858/http://www.lakeland.co.uk/stores/windermere|archive-date=5 May 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Farley Health Products, a subsidiary of the [[H. J. Heinz Company|Heinz Company]], runs a factory in [[Kendal]].<ref name=Heinz>{{cite web|url=http://www.applegate.co.uk/h-j-heinz-co-1207585.html|title=Heinz Kendal|publisher=Applegate|accessdate=16 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224104036/http://www.applegate.co.uk/h-j-heinz-co-1207585.html|archivedate=24 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Tourism===\n[[File:Whinlatter Forest Park Sign.jpg|thumb|right|The entrance to Whinlatter Forest Park]]\n[[File:Way in - geograph.org.uk - 406894.jpg|thumb|right|[[Sizergh Castle and Garden|Sizergh Castle]]]]\n[[File:Muncaster Castle morris edited.jpg|thumb|right|[[Muncaster Castle]]]]\nThe largest and most widespread industry in Cumbria is tourism. The [[Lake District|Lake District National Park]] alone receives some 15.8&nbsp;million visitors every year.<ref name=LakeDistrictstats>{{cite web |url=http://www.lakedistrict.gov.uk/learning/lakedistrictfacts/factsandfigures |title=Lake District National Park |publisher=Lake District National Park |accessdate=16 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019005727/http://www.lakedistrict.gov.uk/learning/lakedistrictfacts/factsandfigures |archivedate=19 October 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Despite this, fewer than 50,000 people reside permanently within the Lake District \u2013 mostly in [[Ambleside]], [[Bowness-on-Windermere]], [[Coniston, Cumbria|Coniston]], [[Keswick, Cumbria|Keswick]], [[Grasmere (village)|Grasmere]] and [[Windermere, Cumbria (town)|Windermere]].<ref name=LakeDistrictstats/> Over 36,000 Cumbrians are employed in the tourism industry which adds \u00a31.1&nbsp;billion a year to the county's economy. The Lake District and county as a whole attracts visitors from across the UK,<ref name=LakeDistrictstats/> Europe, North America and the Far East (particularly Japan).<ref name=LakeDistrictstats/> The tables below show the twenty most-visited attractions in Cumbria in 2009 (please note that not all visitor attractions provided data to Cumbria Tourism who collated the list. Notable examples are [[Furness Abbey]], the [[Lakes Aquarium]] and [[South Lakes Safari Zoo]], the latter of which would almost certainly rank within the top five).<ref name=LakeDistrictstats2>{{cite web |url=http://www.cumbriatourism.org/research/attractions.aspx |title=Lake District National Park|publisher=Cumbria Tourism |accessdate=16 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n{|\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Rank !! Attraction !! Location !! Visitors\n|-\n| 1 || [[Windermere#Steamers, launches and ferries|Windermere Lake Cruises]] || Bowness-on-Windermere || 1,313,807\n|-\n| 2 || Rheged || Penrith || 439,568\n|-\n| 3 || [[Glenridding#Ullswater Steamers|Ullswater Steamers]] || Glenridding || 348,000\n|-\n| 4 || [[Whinlatter Pass|Whinlatter Forest Park and Visitor Centre]] || Whinlatter || 252,762\n|-\n| 5 || [[Tullie House Museum and Art Gallery]] || Carlisle || 251,808\n|-\n| 6 || [[Grizedale Forest|Grizedale Forest Park and Visitor Centre]] || Grizedale || 175,033\n|-\n| 7 || [[Carlisle Cathedral]] || Carlisle || 166,141\n|-\n| 8 || [[Brockhole Lake District Vi