 Wordsworth at 28 by William Shuter2.jpg| [[William Wordsworth]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Geography|<!-- Eurasia -->|Europe|<!-- Western Europe -->|<!-- Northern Europe -->|United Kingdom|England|North West England|Cumbria}}\n\n*[[Anglo-Scottish border]]\n*[[Cumbria County Council]]\n*[[Cumbrian dialect]]\n**[[Barrovian]]\n*[[Cumbric language]]\n*[[Cumbrian toponymy]]\n*[[Etymology of Cumbrian Place Names]]\n* [[Healthcare in Cumbria]]\n*[[List of Cumbria-related topics]]\n*[[High Sheriff of Cumbria|List of High Sheriffs of Cumbria]]\n*[[Lord Lieutenant of Cumbria|List of Lord Lieutenants of Cumbria]]\n*[[Cumbria Constabulary]]\n*[[Cumbria Police and Crime Commissioner]]\n*''[[Outline of England]]''\n*[[Rose Castle]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commonscat-inline|Cumbria}}\n*{{Wikivoyage-inline|Cumbria}}\n\n{{Cumbria}}\n{{England_counties}}\n{{NW_England}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cumbria| ]]\n[[Category:Non-metropolitan counties]]\n[[Category:North West England]]\n[[Category:NUTS 2 statistical regions of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Counties of England established in 1974]]\n", "name_user": "Jamesmcmahon0", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: North/South \u2192 north\u2013south (2), so called \u2192 so-called, Workington based \u2192 Workington-based, \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cumbria"}
{"title_page": "Belford Hall", "text_new": "{{Short description|Grade I listed building, an 18th-century mansion house situated at Belford, Northumberland}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Belford Hall - geograph.org.uk - 1172079.jpg|thumb|Belford Hall.]]\n'''Belford Hall''' is a [[Grade I listed building]], an 18th-century mansion house situated at [[Belford, Northumberland]].\n\nThe Manor of Belford was acquired by the Dixon family in 1726, and in 1752 Abraham Dixon built a mansion house in a [[Palladian style]] to a design by architect [[James Paine (architect)|James Paine]].\n\nIn 1770 heiress Margaret Dixon married William Brown. Their daughter later married Newcastle upon Tyne merchant, Lt. Col. William Clark, [[Deputy Lieutenant]] and [[High Sheriff of Northumberland]]\nwho, in 1818, remodelled the house and added two new wings, with the assistance of architect [[John Dobson (architect)|John Dobson]].\n\nAn extensive  park, created in the mid 18th century, retains several original features and has been designated a [[conservation area]]. An 18th-century folly in the park is a [[Grade II listed building]].\n\nDuring [[World War II]] the Hall was requisitioned by the army and became neglected and dilapidated. In the 1980s it was acquired by the [[Northern Heritage Trust]], renovated, restored, and converted to residential apartments. A golf course was created on a part of the park.\n\n{{coord|55|36|06|N|1|49|31|W|type:city(100)_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n==References==\n* {{NHLE|num=1233314  |desc= Belford Hall|accessdate=30 October 2019}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Country houses in Northumberland]]\n[[Category:Grade I listed buildings in Northumberland]]\n[[Category:Grade I listed houses]]\n[[Category:1752 establishments in Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Palladian architecture]]\n\n\n{{Northumberland-struct-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Belford Hall - geograph.org.uk - 1172079.jpg|thumb|Belford Hall.]]\n'''Belford Hall''' is a [[Grade I listed building]], an 18th-century mansion house situated at [[Belford, Northumberland]].\n\nThe Manor of Belford was acquired by the Dixon family in 1726, and in 1752 Abraham Dixon built a mansion house in a [[Palladian style]] to a design by architect [[James Paine (architect)|James Paine]].\n\nIn 1770 heiress Margaret Dixon married William Brown. Their daughter later married Newcastle upon Tyne merchant, Lt. Col. William Clark, [[Deputy Lieutenant]] and [[High Sheriff of Northumberland]]\nwho, in 1818, remodelled the house and added two new wings, with the assistance of architect [[John Dobson (architect)|John Dobson]].\n\nAn extensive  park, created in the mid 18th century, retains several original features and has been designated a [[conservation area]]. An 18th-century folly in the park is a [[Grade II listed building]].\n\nDuring [[World War II]] the Hall was requisitioned by the army and became neglected and dilapidated. In the 1980s it was acquired by the [[Northern Heritage Trust]], renovated, restored, and converted to residential apartments. A golf course was created on a part of the park.\n\n{{coord|55|36|06|N|1|49|31|W|type:city(100)_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n==References==\n* {{NHLE|num=1233314  |desc= Belford Hall|accessdate=30 October 2019}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Country houses in Northumberland]]\n[[Category:Grade I listed buildings in Northumberland]]\n[[Category:Grade I listed houses]]\n[[Category:1752 establishments in Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Palladian architecture]]\n\n\n{{Northumberland-struct-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Add short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belford_Hall"}
{"title_page": "Belford Hospital", "text_new": "{{Short description|Rural general hospital in Fort William, Lochaber, Scotland}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name        = Belford Hospital\n| Org/Group   = [[NHS Highland]]\n| Image       = Belford Hospital, Fort William (geograph 5818002).jpg\n| Caption     = Belford Hospital\n| Logo        = <!-- optional -->\n| Region      = [[Fort William, Highland|Fort William]], [[Highland (council area)|Highland]]\n| Country     = Scotland\n| HealthCare  = [[NHS Scotland]]\n| Type        = [[Rural general hospital]]\n| Speciality  = <!-- optional -->\n| Emergency   = Yes\n| Helipad     = Yes\n| Affiliation = [[University of Aberdeen School of Medicine|University of Aberdeen]]\n| Beds        = 34\n| Founded     = 1863\n| Closed      = <!-- optional -->\n| Website     = [http://www.nhshighland.scot.nhs.uk/Services/Pages/BelfordHospital.aspx Official Website]\n| Wiki-Links  = <!-- optional, autofilled [List hospitals in <State>] -->\n| map_type    = Scotland Lochaber#Scotland#United Kingdom\n| map_caption = Location in Lochaber##Location in Scotland##Location in United Kingdom\n| coordinates = {{coord|56|49|10|N|5|6|14|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| }}\n\n'''Belford Hospital''', locally known as '''The Belford''', is a [[rural general hospital]] in [[Fort William, Highland|Fort William]], [[Lochaber]], [[Scotland]]. It is managed by [[NHS Highland]].\n\n==History==\nThe original hospital, which was financed by a legacy from  Andrew Belford and designed by Henry Burrell, opened in 1865.<ref name=hh>{{cite web|url=https://historic-hospitals.com/gazetteer/highland/|title=Belford Hospital|publisher=Historic Hospitals|accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref> A prefabricated hospital for fever patients was erected in the grounds in 1893 but, after it burnt down in 1900, was replaced by a more permanent structure in 1901.<ref name=hh/> The main facility was extended following a donation by [[Balfour Beatty]] in 1928.<ref name=hh/> After the existing facility proved inadequate, a new hospital, which was designed by [[Joseph Lea Gleave|Joseph Gleave]] and built by Arnott Macleod, was officially opened by [[Princess Margaret, Countess of Snowdon|Princess Margaret]] and the [[Antony Armstrong-Jones, 1st Earl of Snowdon|Earl of Snowdon]] in April 1965.<ref name=hh/>\n\nWhen the Scottish Executive looked at reorganising rural health care in 2004 there were clear reasons put forward to retain provision of an emergency service at the Belford.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2004/aug/22/NHS.uknews |title=Mountain capital fights to save vital A&E unit |work=[[The Observer]] |last=Martin |first=Lorna |date=22 Aug 2004 |accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref> Following this there were calls to work more closely with the [[Lorn and Islands Hospital]] in [[Oban]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/3705546.stm |title=Hospitals avoid service cutbacks |work=[[BBC News]] |date=1 October 2004 |accessdate=9 June 2014}}</ref> In 2006, following the Kerr report, the Belford was designated a rural general hospital.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhshighland.scot.nhs.uk/news/pages/abrightnewfutureforbelford.aspx |title=A Bright New Future for Belford |publisher=NHS Highland |date=7 February 2006 |accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of November 2009 the surgical and medical wards were merged to form a Combined Assessment Unit (CAU).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhshighland.scot.nhs.uk/news/pages/belfordhospitalservicesredesignedtoimprovedelivery.aspx |title=Belford Hospital Services Redesigned to Improve Delivery |publisher=NHS Highland |date=23 November 2009 |accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nThere are 34 inpatient beds and a 10-bedded day case unit.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.healthcareimprovementscotland.org/our_work/inspecting_and_regulating_care/opah_highland/belford_aug_14.aspx |title=Inspecting and regulating care: Belford Aug 14 |publisher=[[Healthcare Improvement Scotland]] |accessdate=31 May 2015}}</ref> The [[emergency department]] sees around 9,000 patients a year<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhshighland.scot.nhs.uk/services/pages/belfordhospital.aspx |title=Belford Hospital |publisher=[[NHS Highland]] |accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref> making it one of the smallest in [[Scotland]]; however due to its proximity to the outdoor activity centres in the Lochaber region sees proportionally a significant amount of [[Physical trauma|trauma]] prior to transfer to tertiary centres in Edinburgh, Glasgow and Aberdeen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nls.uk/catalogues/online/cnmi/inventories/acc12759.pdf|title=Mountain Rescue Committee Scotland|date=1 January 2008|publisher=National Library of Scotland|accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThere is also a [[midwife]]-led service to provide [[maternity care]]. In September 2009 it achieved stage 1 of the [[Baby Friendly Hospital Initiative|baby-friendly]] accredition programme.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://progress.babyfriendly.org.uk/htables/hospital_detail.asp?hospital=19 |title=Belford Hospital, Fort William |publisher=Baby Friendly Initiative |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref> Although equipped to perform antenatal ultrasound scans, this service has not been offered at the Belford since June 2012, because of a national shortage of appropriately trained staff.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/health/fort-william-mothers-to-be-forced-to-travel-for-scan-1-2906849 |title=Fort William mothers-to-be forced to travel for scan |first=Alistair |last=Munro |work=[[The Scotsman]] |publisher=[[Johnston Press]] |date=24 April 2013 |accessdate=31 May 2015}}</ref> There are also specialist in-patient services for older people.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10418002 |title=Plans for Belford Hospital ward change |work=BBC News |date=28 June 2010 |accessdate=10 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.nhshighland.scot.nhs.uk/Services/Pages/BelfordHospital.aspx Belford Hospital] official webpage on NHS Highland website\n{{Hospitals in NHS Highland}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:NHS Highland]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Highland (council area)]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Highland (council area)]]\n[[Category:Fort William, Highland]]\n[[Category:NHS Scotland hospitals]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name        = Belford Hospital\n| Org/Group   = [[NHS Highland]]\n| Image       = Belford Hospital, Fort William (geograph 5818002).jpg\n| Caption     = Belford Hospital\n| Logo        = <!-- optional -->\n| Region      = [[Fort William, Highland|Fort William]], [[Highland (council area)|Highland]]\n| Country     = Scotland\n| HealthCare  = [[NHS Scotland]]\n| Type        = [[Rural general hospital]]\n| Speciality  = <!-- optional -->\n| Emergency   = Yes\n| Helipad     = Yes\n| Affiliation = [[University of Aberdeen School of Medicine|University of Aberdeen]]\n| Beds        = 34\n| Founded     = 1863\n| Closed      = <!-- optional -->\n| Website     = [http://www.nhshighland.scot.nhs.uk/Services/Pages/BelfordHospital.aspx Official Website]\n| Wiki-Links  = <!-- optional, autofilled [List hospitals in <State>] -->\n| map_type    = Scotland Lochaber#Scotland#United Kingdom\n| map_caption = Location in Lochaber##Location in Scotland##Location in United Kingdom\n| coordinates = {{coord|56|49|10|N|5|6|14|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| }}\n\n'''Belford Hospital''', locally known as '''The Belford''', is a [[rural general hospital]] in [[Fort William, Highland|Fort William]], [[Lochaber]], [[Scotland]]. It is managed by [[NHS Highland]].\n\n==History==\nThe original hospital, which was financed by a legacy from  Andrew Belford and designed by Henry Burrell, opened in 1865.<ref name=hh>{{cite web|url=https://historic-hospitals.com/gazetteer/highland/|title=Belford Hospital|publisher=Historic Hospitals|accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref> A prefabricated hospital for fever patients was erected in the grounds in 1893 but, after it burnt down in 1900, was replaced by a more permanent structure in 1901.<ref name=hh/> The main facility was extended following a donation by [[Balfour Beatty]] in 1928.<ref name=hh/> After the existing facility proved inadequate, a new hospital, which was designed by [[Joseph Lea Gleave|Joseph Gleave]] and built by Arnott Macleod, was officially opened by [[Princess Margaret, Countess of Snowdon|Princess Margaret]] and the [[Antony Armstrong-Jones, 1st Earl of Snowdon|Earl of Snowdon]] in April 1965.<ref name=hh/>\n\nWhen the Scottish Executive looked at reorganising rural health care in 2004 there were clear reasons put forward to retain provision of an emergency service at the Belford.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2004/aug/22/NHS.uknews |title=Mountain capital fights to save vital A&E unit |work=[[The Observer]] |last=Martin |first=Lorna |date=22 Aug 2004 |accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref> Following this there were calls to work more closely with the [[Lorn and Islands Hospital]] in [[Oban]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/3705546.stm |title=Hospitals avoid service cutbacks |work=[[BBC News]] |date=1 October 2004 |accessdate=9 June 2014}}</ref> In 2006, following the Kerr report, the Belford was designated a rural general hospital.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhshighland.scot.nhs.uk/news/pages/abrightnewfutureforbelford.aspx |title=A Bright New Future for Belford |publisher=NHS Highland |date=7 February 2006 |accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of November 2009 the surgical and medical wards were merged to form a Combined Assessment Unit (CAU).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhshighland.scot.nhs.uk/news/pages/belfordhospitalservicesredesignedtoimprovedelivery.aspx |title=Belford Hospital Services Redesigned to Improve Delivery |publisher=NHS Highland |date=23 November 2009 |accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nThere are 34 inpatient beds and a 10-bedded day case unit.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.healthcareimprovementscotland.org/our_work/inspecting_and_regulating_care/opah_highland/belford_aug_14.aspx |title=Inspecting and regulating care: Belford Aug 14 |publisher=[[Healthcare Improvement Scotland]] |accessdate=31 May 2015}}</ref> The [[emergency department]] sees around 9,000 patients a year<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhshighland.scot.nhs.uk/services/pages/belfordhospital.aspx |title=Belford Hospital |publisher=[[NHS Highland]] |accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref> making it one of the smallest in [[Scotland]]; however due to its proximity to the outdoor activity centres in the Lochaber region sees proportionally a significant amount of [[Physical trauma|trauma]] prior to transfer to tertiary centres in Edinburgh, Glasgow and Aberdeen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nls.uk/catalogues/online/cnmi/inventories/acc12759.pdf|title=Mountain Rescue Committee Scotland|date=1 January 2008|publisher=National Library of Scotland|accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThere is also a [[midwife]]-led service to provide [[maternity care]]. In September 2009 it achieved stage 1 of the [[Baby Friendly Hospital Initiative|baby-friendly]] accredition programme.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://progress.babyfriendly.org.uk/htables/hospital_detail.asp?hospital=19 |title=Belford Hospital, Fort William |publisher=Baby Friendly Initiative |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref> Although equipped to perform antenatal ultrasound scans, this service has not been offered at the Belford since June 2012, because of a national shortage of appropriately trained staff.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/health/fort-william-mothers-to-be-forced-to-travel-for-scan-1-2906849 |title=Fort William mothers-to-be forced to travel for scan |first=Alistair |last=Munro |work=[[The Scotsman]] |publisher=[[Johnston Press]] |date=24 April 2013 |accessdate=31 May 2015}}</ref> There are also specialist in-patient services for older people.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10418002 |title=Plans for Belford Hospital ward change |work=BBC News |date=28 June 2010 |accessdate=10 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.nhshighland.scot.nhs.uk/Services/Pages/BelfordHospital.aspx Belford Hospital] official webpage on NHS Highland website\n{{Hospitals in NHS Highland}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:NHS Highland]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Highland (council area)]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Highland (council area)]]\n[[Category:Fort William, Highland]]\n[[Category:NHS Scotland hospitals]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Add short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belford_Hospital"}
